references: While previous work (see e.g.  [57, 10, 28]) often assumes that the adversary has access to a reference dataset (typically sampled from the same distribution as the target dataset), we do not make such assumption. Instead, we assume that the adversary is partially informed: the adversary has access to X𝑋X (the adversary’s auxiliary information), but not to the secret attribute values 𝐲𝐲\mathbf{y}. We call X𝑋X the matrix of quasi-identifiers, representing information that may be publicly available through additional data releases. Table 1 provides a summary of the notation and the adversary’s knowledge. We motivate the use of this threat model in Section 7.3.
